plementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Prioritize system restoration to minimize financial losses, as data preservation can be handled later. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Outsource all incident response activities to a specialized cybersecurity firm. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Ignore the legal aspect since it is not directly related to information security. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.'),
  ('CISA-00008', 5, 'Medium', 'Data Classification', 'During an audit of a healthcare provider, the IS auditor discovers that all data, including publicly available information, is classified as ''Highly Confidential''. Which of the following is the MOST significant risk associated with this practice?', 'Increased administrative overhead due to overly restrictive access controls.', 'Insufficient resources allocated to protecting truly sensitive data.', 'Elevated risk of data breaches due to complex security configurations.', 'Reduced employee productivity due to strict data handling procedures.', 'B', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Insufficient resources allocated to protecting truly sensitive data.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Increased administrative overhead due to overly restrictive access controls