  ('CISA-00018', 1, 'Hard', 'Professional Ethics and Standards', 'During an IT audit, the auditor discovers that a close personal friend works in the IT department being audited. The friend is not in a management position, but has significant responsibilities related to the systems under review. What is the MOST appropriate action for the auditor to take?', 'Continue with the audit as planned, exercising professional skepticism and documenting the relationship.', 'Disclose the relationship to the audit manager and request to be removed from the audit engagement.', 'Inform the friend of the audit findings before reporting them to management.', 'Adjust the audit procedures to minimize interaction with the friend.', 'B', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Disclose the relationship to the audit manager and request to be removed from the audit engagement.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for fut