  ('CISA-00023', 4, 'Medium', 'Incident Management', 'An IS auditor is reviewing the incident management process. The auditor notices that user training on incident reporting is minimal. What is the MOST significant risk associated with this deficiency?', 'Delayed incident identification and response.', 'Increased workload for the IT support team.', 'Inaccurate documentation of incident details.', 'Non-compliance with regulatory reporting requirements.', 'A', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (A): Delayed incident identification and response.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option B: Increased workload for the IT support team. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  