per authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option B: Evaluate the cost-effectiveness of the cloud-based solution compared to the previous on-premise solution. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Assess the training provided to IT staff on using the new backup and recovery system. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Perform a full data recovery test to ensure the solution meets the organization''s recovery time objectives (RTOs). → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.'),
  ('CISA-00035', 4, 'Medium', 'Incident Management', 'During a review of the incident management process, an IS auditor notices that incident closure times are consistently exceeding established targets. The auditor should FIRST:', 'Recommend implementing a new incident management system with automated workflows.', 'Review the incident classification and prioritization procedures to identify potential bottlenecks.', 'Interview IT staff to determine the root causes of the delays in incident resolution.', 'Compare incident resolution times with industry benchmarks to assess overall performance.', 'B', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Review the incident classification and prioritization procedures to identify potential bottlenecks.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Recommend implementing a new incident manageme