  ('CISA-00087', 1, 'Hard', 'Audit Program Development', 'An IS auditor is developing an audit program to review the cybersecurity incident response plan (IRP) of a large organization. The organization operates in a highly regulated industry and has a complex IT infrastructure. Which of the following steps is MOST important for the IS auditor to take when developing the audit program?', 'Focus solely on testing the technical aspects of the IRP, such as the effectiveness of intrusion detection systems and firewall rules.', 'Base the audit program solely on industry best practices and compliance frameworks, such as NIST and ISO standards.', 'Tailor the audit program to the organization''s specific IT infrastructure, regulatory requirements, and identified cybersecurity risks.', 'Delegate the development of the audit program to a junior auditor to gain experience and reduce the overall audit cost.', 'C', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (C): Tailor the audit program to the organization''s specific IT infrastructure, regulatory requirements, and identified cybersecurity risks.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Focus solely on testing the technical aspects of the IRP, such as the effectiveness of intrusion detection systems and firewall rules. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option B: Base the audit program solely on industry best practices and compliance frameworks, such as NIST and ISO standards. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Delegate the development of the audit program to a junior auditor to gain experience and reduce the overall audit cost. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.', 'Tailoring the audit program to the organization''s specific context is paramount. This includes understanding the IT infrastructure, regulatory landscape, and unique cybersecurity risks faced by the organization. A tailored program ensures that the audit focuses on the most critical areas and provides relevant and actionable insights.', 'See reasoning above for explanation of correct vs incorrect choices', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (C): Tailor the audit program to the organization''s specific IT infrastructure, regulatory requirements, and identified cybersecurity risks.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately