inding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Increased cost associated with implementing additional encryption. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Performance degradation due to additional encryption overhead. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Difficulty in auditing the cloud provider''s security practices. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.'),
  ('CISA-00148', 5, 'Hard', 'Incident Response', 'During a review of an organization''s incident response plan, the auditor observes that the plan primarily focuses on technical recovery and restoration. There is minimal guidance on communication with stakeholders, including customers, regulators, and the media. Which of the following should the auditor recommend as the MOST critical improvement to the incident response plan?', 'Implementing automated malware analysis tools.', 'Developing a comprehensive communication strategy that addresses internal and external stakeholders.', 'Conducting regular penetration testing exercises.', 'Establishing a dedicated security operations center (SOC).', 'B', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Developing a comprehensive communication strategy that addresses internal and external stakeholders.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits 