  ('CISA-00219', 4, 'Hard', 'Change Management & Incident Response', 'During a review of a recent critical system outage, the CISA auditor discovers that the incident response plan failed to adequately address communication protocols with third-party vendors responsible for key infrastructure components. While internal escalation procedures were followed, the vendors were not promptly notified, delaying resolution. What is the MOST appropriate action for the CISA auditor?', 'Recommend revising the incident response plan to explicitly include communication protocols for third-party vendors, emphasizing notification timelines and escalation procedures.', 'Issue a finding recommending the IT department replace the third-party vendors with those who have a proven track record of faster response times.', 'Certify that the internal incident response procedures were adequate and focus on improving internal communication to prevent future outages.', 'Advise the organization to negotiate more stringent SLAs with the existing third-party vendors and penalize them for the outage.', 'A', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (A): Recommend revising the incident response plan to explicitly include communication protocols for third-party vendors, emphasizing notification timelines and escalation procedures.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommen