  ('CISA-00228', 3, 'Medium', 'Project Management - Risk Management', 'An organization is implementing a new enterprise resource planning (ERP) system. During a review of the project''s risk register, the IS auditor notes that the risk related to ''insufficient user training'' is identified but has a low impact score. The auditor knows that previous system implementations have been significantly hampered by inadequate user training. What should the IS auditor do?', 'Accept the risk assessment as documented since it is based on the project team''s evaluation.', 'Recommend that the project team reassess the impact score for the ''insufficient user training'' risk, considering historical data and potential consequences.', 'Independently develop and deliver user training materials to mitigate the risk.', 'Report the risk to senior management as a critical project failure point.', 'B', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Recommend that the project team reassess the impact score for the ''insufficient user training'' risk, considering historical data and potential consequences.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, h