  ('CISA-00263', 2, 'Hard', 'IT Investment Prioritization', 'An IS auditor is reviewing the IT investment prioritization process at a manufacturing company. The auditor observes that IT projects are primarily prioritized based on their alignment with short-term business goals and immediate cost savings. Long-term strategic alignment, innovation, and potential impacts on IT infrastructure resilience are given less consideration. This approach has resulted in a backlog of technical debt and increased vulnerability to cybersecurity threats. What should the IS auditor recommend to BEST improve the IT investment prioritization process?', 'Mandate that all IT projects undergo a comprehensive cybersecurity risk assessment before being considered for funding.', 'Implement a formal IT balanced scorecard that incorporates strategic, financial, customer, and internal process perspectives.', 'Establish a dedicated IT innovation fund to encourage the development and implementation of new technologies.', 'Develop a detailed IT infrastructure roadmap that outlines the company''s long-term technology needs and priorities.', 'B', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Implement a formal IT balanced scorecard that incorporates strategic, financial, customer, and internal process perspectives.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Mandate that all IT projects undergo a comprehensive cybersecurity risk assessment before being considered for funding. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Establish a dedicated IT innovation fund to encourage the development and implementation of new technologies. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Develop a detailed IT infrastructure roadmap that outlines the company''s long-term technology needs and priorities. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.', 'Implementing a formal IT balanced scorecard approach will best address the issue. By incorporating strategic, financial, customer, and internal process perspectives, the organization will be forced to consider factors beyond short-term cost savings and immediate business goals. This will provide a more holistic view of the potential benefits and risks associated with each IT investment.', 'See reasoning above for explanation of correct vs incorrect choices', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Implement a formal IT balanced scorecard that incorporates strategic, financial, customer, and internal process perspectives.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Mandate that all IT projects undergo a comprehensive cybersecurity risk assessment before being considered for funding. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Establish a dedicated IT innovation fund to encourage the development and implementation of new technologies. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Develop a detailed IT infrastructure roadmap that outlines the company''s long-term technology needs and priorities. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisi