pplies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Recommend that the PMO perform a detailed data migration feasibility study to validate the initial estimates and quantify the potential impact of the error. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.'),
  ('CISA-00275', 1, 'Hard', 'Audit Evidence and Documentation', 'An IS auditor is performing a post-implementation review of a newly implemented customer relationship management (CRM) system. During the audit, the auditor discovers that key user acceptance testing (UAT) documentation, specifically the signed-off test scripts and associated results, are missing. The project manager explains that the documents were accidentally deleted due to a storage migration error and are not recoverable. What is the MOST appropriate course of action for the IS auditor?', 'Issue a qualified opinion stating that the system''s implementation cannot be fully validated due to the missing UAT documentation.', 'Rely on alternative evidence, such as user interviews and system logs, to compensate for the missing UAT documentation and determine if the CRM system is functioning as intended.', 'Expand the audit scope to include a thorough review of the system development lifecycle (SDLC) processes to identify weaknesses in change management and data backup procedures.', 'Immediately halt the audit and demand that the project manager provide a written attestation confirming that the system meets all specified requirements.', 'B', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Rely on alternative evidence, such as user interviews and system logs, to compensate for the missing UAT documentation and determine if the CRM system is functioning as intended.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Issue a qualified opinion stating that the system''s implementation cannot be fully validated due to the missing UAT documentation. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Expand the audit scope to include a thorough review of the system development lifecycle (SDLC) processes to identify weaknesses in change management and data backup procedures. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Immediately halt the audit and demand that the project manager provide a written attestation confirming that the system meets all specified requirements. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.', 'In the absence of primary evidence, the IS auditor should seek alternative evidence to gain assurance over the system''s functionality and implementation. User interviews and system logs can provide valuable insights into the system''s operation and user experience, helping to compensate for the missing UAT documentation.', 'See reasoning above for explanation of correct vs incorrect choices', '✅ C